```

In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command is placed right after the `\maketitle` command in the document preamble. The table of contents is generated automatically based on the defined sections (`\section` and `\subsection`) and their hierarchical structure. No additional packages or commands are needed to create the table of contents, as this functionality is built into the `book` and `article` document classes by default.

Creating a chessboard diagram from a FEN (Fenwick Notation) in LaTeX involves using a package like `chessboard` or `chesspic`, which specifically caters to drawing chessboards. Here, I'll demonstrate using the `chessboard` package.

First, make sure you have the package installed. If not, you can get it from CTAN (https://www.ctan.org/pkg/chessboard).

Here's a LaTeX code snippet that sets up a chessboard based on a given FEN notation:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

% Define a command to set up the board based on a FEN notation
\newcommand{\drawchessboard}[1]{%
  \chessboard[%
    width=8cm, % Adjust the size as needed
    position of moves={(1,1)}, % Top-left starting position for moves (1-based indexing)
    #1 % Pass the FEN notation as an argument
  ]
}

% Your FEN notation goes here
\def\initialFEN{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/2p5/3P4/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}

\begin{document}
% Draw the chessboard with the initial FEN notation
\drawchessboard{\initialFEN}
\end{document}
```

Replace `\initialFEN` with the desired FEN notation. The `chessboard` package will automatically place pieces on the board based on the given notation.

